%N A209932 Numbers k such that smallest digit of all divisors of k is 0.
%C A209932 Also numbers k such that smallest digit of concatenation of all divisors of k (A037278 or A176558) is 0.
%C A209932 First term not in A011540 is a(40) = 212. - Corrected by _Robert Israel_, Jul 08 2026
%H A209932 Robert Israel, <a href="/A209932/b209932.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A209932 Number 214 is in sequence because smallest digit of all divisors of 214 (1, 2, 107, 214) is 0.
%p A209932 filter:= proc(n)
%p A209932    ormap(t -> member(0,convert(t,base,10)), NumberTheory:-Divisors(n))
%p A209932 end proc:
%p A209932 select(filter, [$1..1000]); # _Robert Israel_, Jul 08 2026
%t A209932 Select[Range[400],Min[Flatten[IntegerDigits/@Divisors[#]]]==0&] (* _Harvey P. Dale_, Dec 03 2021 *)
%o A209932 (Python)
%o A209932 from sympy import divisors
%o A209932 def ok(k): return "0" in str(k) or any("0" in str(d) for d in divisors(k, generator=True))
%o A209932 print([k for k in range(1, 401) if ok(k)]) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Jul 08 2026
%Y A209932 Cf. A209929 (smallest digit of all divisors of n), complement of A209931.
